static.solution:
\text{Mike and Karen are tall.} 




Let p be the statement \text{Mike is tall} 


Let q be the statement \text{Karen is tall}



First, translate the statement into formal logic. 


In this statement, p is true, and q is true. Therefore, the correct answer is p  and  q, or p\wedge q.



Now, negate the statement. 


\mathbin{\sim} (p\wedge q) 


\equiv ( \mathbin{\sim} p\vee \mathbin{\sim} q) 


Thus, the answer is 


\mathbin{\sim} p\vee \mathbin{\sim} q



Recall what p and q represent: 




\text{p: Mike is tall} 


\text{q: Karen is tall} 




From \mathbin{\sim} p\vee \mathbin{\sim} q, we get 


\text{Mike is not tall, or Karen is not tall.}

\text{If Mary fails her classes, then she cannot graduate.} 




\text{p: Mary fails her classes} 


\text{q: Mary can graduate} 




In this statement, if p is true, then q is false. This is an implies relationship. Thus, the answer is 


p\rightarrow \mathbin{\sim} q



Now, negate the statement. 


In order to negate this statement, first translate it into an or statement to get rid of the implies operator. 


p\rightarrow \mathbin{\sim} q\equiv \mathbin{\sim} p\vee \mathbin{\sim} q 


\mathbin{\sim} ( \mathbin{\sim} p\vee \mathbin{\sim} q) 


\equiv p\wedge q 


Thus, the answer is p\wedge q



Recall what p and q represent: 




\text{p: Mary fails her classes} 


\text{q: Mary can graduate} 




From p\wedge q, we get 


\text{Mary fails her classes, and she can graduate.}
